gomodel:SYNGO_2235  a     owl:Ontology ;
        rdfs:comment      "Rationale: Fig.1: \"Rab8 and Rab11 are strictly required for LTP.\"\nOverexpression of Rab11dn prevents induction of LTP but does not alter basal synaptic transmission.\n\nFig.2: \"Rab8 and Rab11 mediate separate anatomical steps in the synaptic delivery of AMPA receptors\"\n\nNote: The endosomal element of the annotation was based on author intent; Rab11 is a marker protein of the early endosomal compartment and is a well known regulator of endosomal trafficking. The Rab8 protein is postulated to act in a transport step after Rab11 (early endosome). As such the Rab8 function is also part of the endosome-to-plasma membrane transport pathway:\n\n\"Specifically, these data suggest that GluR1 is sequentially transported through Rab11-driven endosomes for its regulated translocation from dendrites into spines and then through Rab8-driven compartments for its functional insertion into synaptic membranes.\". Experimental description: - Slice cultures: species not stated\n- Species of overexpressed DN Rab forms are not mentioned in this paper. Authors were contacted ( Jose A. Esteban [jaesteban@cbm.csic.es].. 14/12/2017)Author answered:\n\n\"Dear Pim,\nSure. Here you have the information:\n- Rab4dn: rat\n- Rab5dn: human\n- Rab8dn: rat\n- Rab11dn: rat\nBest,\nJose\"" ;
        lego:modelstate   "production" ;
        dc:contributor    "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-5615-1014" ;
        dc:date           "2018-01-24" ;
        dc:title          "SYNGO_BP_2235" ;
        pav:providedBy    "https://syngo.vu.nl" ;
        biolink:in_taxon  "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/NCBITaxon_10116" .

